## Summary

I've completed your request. The briefing on the agent-native application 
paradigm has been written and saved to **`agent-native-paradigm-briefing.md`**.

The document provides a comprehensive overview of:
- **What agent-native applications are** — autonomous LLM-backed agents 
reasoning and delegating within declared envelopes
- **Core components** — the agent mesh (infrastructure enforcement layer), 
declarative specification (permission boundaries), and hybrid orchestrator 
(control plane)
- **Agent flexibility** — both native (LLM) and script (deterministic Python) 
agents running through the same mesh
- **Permission and safety** — how declarative envelopes replace prompt-based 
instructions, enforced through six key safety invariants
- **Delegation semantics** — stateless children, sequential vs. parallel 
spawning, and how the call stack becomes the delegation tree
- **Why this matters** — infrastructure-enforced rules eliminate ambiguity that 
natural language cannot guarantee

The briefing uses practical rationale throughout and connects each concept to 
real implementation concerns.
